Migrate from Redis to SQLite per-blog database [Decision needed]
- evaluate feasibility of storing one SQLite database per blog in data/blogs/{blogID}/blog.db
- assess performance implications (memory usage, query speed, connection management)
- design hybrid approach: SQLite per-blog for blog-scoped data + small Redis/master DB for global lookups
- identify all global queries that span multiple blogs and plan migration strategy
- estimate memory savings vs current Redis approach
- consider connection pooling/lazy opening strategy for managing many SQLite connections
- evaluate concurrent write patterns and SQLite locking behavior
- create proof-of-concept migration for entry storage
- benchmark query performance comparison
- document migration path and breaking changes required

Move blog files from EBS to S3 for cost reduction and improved scalability [Decision needed]
- goal: lower storage costs + transfer from $200/month to $20/month, no charges for unused GB disk space, lower cost of S3 vs EBS, no issue of 'running out of space'
- general considerations: what s3 category to use? standard? 1 zone express? latency is important for some use-cases
- static files (e.g. thumbnails) are more long term infrequent access though (because of CDN)
- do we re-organize how files are stored? one bucket per site?
- make sure s3 versioning is disabled?
- how to back up? maybe have a special bucket for blog folder data? everything else is downstream of the folder
- come up with plan for static files directory: rewrite docx, odt, clients to use a temp dir, then create an abstract helper function which can upload to s3
- write script to sync existing static files to s3
- we probably don't need a caching layer for static files since static files will end up in CDN storage after first request
- come up with plan for blog files directory: abstract write/read from blog directory, we probably need a caching layer using instance SSD as LRU cache of say 10GB
- rewrite git client as follows: store bare repos on s3 as source of truth, on push fetch bare repo from s3 and store on instance SSD in cache, after push resync bare repo to s3
- other ideas: I thought about using an s3fs but it seems risky and likely too slow
- once this is done, the nginx + node server is stateless and could be replicated easily across aws regions

Use Bunny CDN tag-based cache purging [Decision needed]
- leverage bunny tag based caching to perform full blogID based purges
- https://bunny.net/blog/introducing-tag-based-cdn-cache-purging/
- this would improve cache invalidation strategy

